  "texts": [
    "):(40) tr (h -1 Ric h)E = -1 2 ⟨δ(E), [•, •]⟩ h, ∀ E ∈ End(𝔫).Here[•, •] ∈ Λ 2 𝔫 * ⊗ 𝔫 is the Lie bracket of 𝔫, δ(E)(•, •) = -E[•, •] + [E•, •] + [•, E•] ∈ Λ 2 𝔫 * ⊗ 𝔫,and the inner product is the natural extension of h to the Λ 2 𝔫 * ⊗ 𝔫.",
    "Notice that δ(D) = 0 precisely when D ∈ Der(𝔫).",
    "As an immediate application of (40) we see that the Ricci endomorphism is orthogonal to derivations, thus the nilsoliton derivation D from Proposition A.2 must satisfy (41) tr D 2 = λ tr D. 12β.",
    "If D ∈ Der(𝔫) is such that [D + D T, β] = 0 (this holds in particular if [D, β] = 0), then L:= D + D T ∈ Der(𝔫) and tr (adU)L = 0, ∀ U ∈ 𝔫.",
    "Taking E = [D, D T] in (40) (transpose with respect to h), standard properties of δ and the extended inner products (see [LL14, §7]) give 0 = tr[β, D + D T]D T = tr β[D, D T] = -1 2 ⟨δ([D, D T]), [•, •]⟩h = -1 2 ∥δ(D T)∥ 2 h.It follows that D T ∈ Der(𝔫), and the same for L. To see that the trace against adU vanishes, consider the orthogonal decomposition𝔫 = 𝔫 1 ⊕ • • • ⊕ 𝔫 k, where 𝔫 2 ⊕ • • • 𝔫 k = [𝔫, 𝔫], 𝔫 3 ⊕ • • • 𝔫 k = [𝔫, [𝔫, 𝔫]], and so on."
